DO NOT MIX TOOTHPASTE, PAINT, AND NAILPOLISH TO MAKE PLASTER! Holy GOD who came up with that!? "I put a hole in my wall, so I tried this hack. Now I have a hole in my walll and have to sand and repaint it as well because there is a lumpy mess of garbage stuck to it!"

I hope I can figure out how to tell this story because the M.C. of the dream, who I can be certain was not me, has quite a story that needs to be told about putting on a show that isn't everything the audience wants, but everything they need.

Waking up early lets us come up with our own waking endings, rational ones that we WANT to happen. Seeing them through, however, usually ends with our dreams telling us the story we need at the time, even if, when we wake up, we aren't sure it is the one that we wanted.

Woke up from a nap that fully encapsulated a story that I jotted down in my dream journal of stories. It's rare to see a dream's ending, though I've found that sometimes it's sadder to see how they end, in a bitter-sweet way, than thinking of how they could of.

—tail shielding his smaller frame from the world.

Just before he fully loses consciousness, he decides then and there that if Deku tries to take Eijirou away, he’ll tear the fuckers head off. Who needs a human anyways.

“Of course,” Eijirou replies, a slight purr in his tone.

His tongue is rough, tough on the grime that still encases Katsuki’s wounds, but so soft and warm that Katsuki barely acknowledges the pain. He falls asleep with Eijirou wrapped around him,—

Katsuki isn’t sure when he started purring, but he doesn’t stop it as he moves to push himself into Eijirou’s side.

“Katsuki, your wounds, I—” 

“Clean me.” The demand is sharp and soft.

The nose against Katsuki’s own is cool and soothing as it presses to his and rubs slightly, making every muscle relax. 

“You’re the most alpha feline I’ve ever met. Even with kittens, I’m sure you’ll be able to take him down.”
“Of course,” Eijirou says as he moves in close, body not quite touching Katsuki’s, but close enough that he can feel the warmth. It soothes the wounds without aggravating them with friction.

“When you fight him again, I’ll be there. Make sure the other bastards don’t try to jump in.”

That surprises him more than anything.

“Y-you’d let me fight him myself?”

“Shhh, it’s okay,” Eijirou says as he moves in slowly. “It’s okay.” He sniffs over him then, finding each cut and giving tentative licks now and again; not quite cleaning, just memorizing. Katsuki finds himself thankful for that. He can clean his own wounds, damn it.

“I want to fill you with kittens and help you raise them; watch them play and get fat on your milk.” 

Katsuki’s tail starts to flatten; his hackles begin to fall. The cuts on his body ache and he just...he just wants warmth around him.

—challenging on instinct alone while he aches to feel the warmth of the other touching him.

“It was one time.”

“And I want many more,” Eijirou responds as he comes closer, lowering himself as he does.

“Because you’re my mate,” he says, voice coming out sterner than even Katsuki expects. “You’re my mate, and I want to make sure you’re okay.” He moves forward then, not seeming to care as Katsuki puffs up; —

Eijirou faulters, “I-I thought you might want some company.”

“Why the fuck would I want that?”

“Because you’re my…” Eijirou pauses, half crouched, ears laid back and eyes wide as he looks at Katsuki. 

“Spit it out, fur-for-brains.”

Katsuki’s own Persian coat does something similar, but it doesn’t look like it would stab into you. It’s too fucking /soft/ for that.

“The hell are you here for,” he grumbles, curling tighter as he glares. His fur is on end, but only because he’s forcing it.
In fact, he feels a strange sense of peace slip into him as Eijirou comes towards him. He’s a larger breed; main-coon most likely, with hair that sticks out in spike-like clumps.

Finding an alpha worth his time hadn’t been a part of him finding his freedom. 

“Does it hurt?” The red-headed hybrid with the scarred up eye and ragged tail slips into the window with a quiet thud. How he’d found him, Katsuki isn’t sure, but he’s not mad.

Bastard barely ever noticed, he was gone so often, and he had given that damn ‘Deku’ more scars than the human’s job. Still, Katsuki had always gotten out; had always gotten into a fight; had always won.

Being covered in scratches means one thing to Katsuki, and that’s that he doesn’t want to be fucking touched! At least, it did before, when he was nothing but a lone hybrid stalking the streets; constantly dodging the catchers whenever his owner had realized he was missing.

“Would you like to join me?” he heard in his mind.

A resounding ‘yes’ echoed in his brain before he could stop it.

“When the hell did I invite you?” Neito asked, not paying attention to the small ‘quarrel’ between the other elf and dwarf that had distracted the rest.

“The moment you thought of me.”

Neito’s face burned as he stared up into the other’s eyes.

He was surprised when he saw a slight tint of pink on Shinsou’s cheeks.

“Mind Whisperer,” he muttered. “Right.”

“Only when you invite me.”

“Everything alright, Master Monoma?” The purr of a voice stilled him in his tracks, and with a glance, he found Indigo looking down upon him. “I promise I won’t let you go astray.”

/“My dick says otherwise,”/ his brain said quickly.

“I’ll just blow away the bastards to make us a path.”

Eijirou beamed, “And you can use me as the cannonball.”

Neito wanted to groan. Really? These would be his traveling mates?

“And I’ll make sure you’ve got an unwavering shield,” the dwarf piped up. “I’m Eijirou Kirishima of the Morian dwarves.”

“Shut up,” the blonde elf, Katsuki grunted. “Like we care.”

“Hey, when you’re backed in a corner, you’ll want me there.”

“Then, these will be the ones who accompany you.” She motioned to them, and when Neito saw Deku grin at the Indigo-haired elf, his heart was struck with jealousy.

“My men, Hitoshi Shinsou, the Whisperer of Minds, and Katsuki Bakugou, of the Erupting Palms will join you.”

—; and Deku along with another human who stood tall and wore the helm of a knight.

“Will you continue to take the ring?” the Lady of Midnight asked him, the elf Aizawa standing behind her.

“Of course,” he replied as he puffed out his chest.

He had no need to get mixed up with such idiocy.

Yet, when he came down to the group the next day, he found the indigo haired elf standing beside a rather brash looking blond; a red-haired dwarf who looked like his hair and beard were carved from rubies; his friends—

Neito’s ears blazed with heat, though he refused to turn around.

“And you’re a bastard.”

He hated himself just a little for the words, but not enough to turn back and apologize. Elves were supposed to be holier-than-thou, after all.

He could hear the intake of surprise as he stalked away towards the quarters given to him for the night. The Lady of Midnight had made sure they were all well taken care of.

“You’re a special one,” he heard murmured behind him.

“Does my appearance please you, little one?”

He almost said yes. Almost. It was the quip at the end that broke the spell.

“You’re as lovely as a troll statue,” he spat as he quickly turned, cheeks blazing.

Neito found himself unable to speak, mouth agape as the elf smiled down at him. He felt like he could not speak. His tongue was not his own, his heart blocking anything that could come out. Those eyes were pulling him in. More tantalizing than any ring.

Neito threw a glare over his shoulder only to falter. He was so close, deep eyes the color of the sky just before the sun is swallowed into the earth; indigo so deep with twinkles of purples and greys that the stars themselves would be at home.

Instead, he straightened his vest and started to walk away, doing his best to keep his steps quiet even though his large feet made that quite hard to do without leaves.

“Am I now?”

Like all of the elves he’d seen so far, this one was quite beautiful. Alabaster skin, silken hair, though his stood out strikingly; like fresh dandelion fluff.

“Because you’re a pompous prick.” The insult came before he could think on it, though Neito did little to right it.

Neito had just about fallen over the rail he was so startled. The night had been so quiet, and he hadn’t heard the elf’s feet in the least.

“Are you trying to kill me?” he hissed as he managed to keep himself from falling over.

“Now why would you think something like that?”

And then Neito had woken in a lavish world of white oak and silver saplings; a world with an indigo haired elf that disappeared into the shadows as easily as a cat.

“You must really be serious about this, Master Monoma.”
Just the trek through the woods had been hard enough; the human ranger ‘Deku’ taking them out into the woods, protecting them. Still, the wraiths had come. They had almost died!
Still, when the blood-wizard Vlad came to him and asked for his help, he couldn’t say no. He had begrudgingly gone, Tetsutetsu and Kendo following close with Awase not far behind.
Leave the shire. Put himself in danger. Die, most likely, or be scarred for the rest of his life and wake up at odd hours screaming like his uncle. None of it sounded appealing.

But then he’d gone off and found the damn thing, telling everyone about his exploits whenever possible. And while they were fanciful and captivating, the idea of going on such an adventure was still such an idiotic idea to Monoma.

—, and the fact that it fell to a hobbit’s shoulders was a wonder in itself. The fact that it fell to the Monoma line was even more so. They had always been such a stand-up, upstanding family before his great-uncle.

Neito had never wanted to do something so idiotic as go on a quest to some godforsaken mountain. It made little sense to him, but doing so meant getting rid of one of the most powerful artifacts in the land—
